+\subsection{Bounded-Domain Biot--Savart Admissibility}
+        \label{subsec:bounded_domain_biot_savart}
+
+        \textbf{[ORTHODOX OPERATOR FOUNDATION].}
+        For a smooth vector field \(\mathbf V\) supported in a bounded smooth domain
+        \(\Omega\subset\mathbb R^3\), define
+        \begin{align}
+            \operatorname{BS}[\mathbf V](\mathbf y)
+            :=
+            \frac{1}{4\pi}
+            \int_\Omega
+            \mathbf V(\mathbf x)\times
+            \frac{\mathbf y-\mathbf x}{|\mathbf y-\mathbf x|^3}
+            \,d^3x.
+            \label{eq:canon_bounded_biot_savart}
+        \end{align}
+        Its curl contains explicit source and boundary corrections:
+        \begin{align}
+            \nabla_{\mathbf y}\times\operatorname{BS}[\mathbf V]
+            ={}&
+            \mathbf 1_\Omega(\mathbf y)\mathbf V(\mathbf y)
+            +
+            \frac{1}{4\pi}\nabla_{\mathbf y}
+            \int_\Omega
+            \frac{\nabla_{\mathbf x}\cdot\mathbf V(\mathbf x)}
+                 {|\mathbf y-\mathbf x|}
+            \,d^3x
+            \notag\\
+            &-
+            \frac{1}{4\pi}\nabla_{\mathbf y}
+            \int_{\partial\Omega}
+            \frac{\mathbf V(\mathbf x)\cdot\mathbf n(\mathbf x)}
+                 {|\mathbf y-\mathbf x|}
+            \,dA_x.
+            \label{eq:canon_biot_savart_curl_corrections}
+        \end{align}
+        Consequently,
+        \begin{align}
+            \nabla\times\operatorname{BS}[\mathbf V]
+            =
+            \mathbf V
+            \quad\text{in }\Omega
+            \quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
+            \nabla\cdot\mathbf V=0,
+            \quad
+            \mathbf V\cdot\mathbf n=0
+            \text{ on }\partial\Omega.
+            \label{eq:canon_biot_savart_left_inverse_gate}
+        \end{align}
+        These conditions are necessary as well as sufficient
+        \cite{CantarellaDeTurckGluck2001BiotSavart}.
+
+        The same source establishes
+        \begin{align}
+            \ker\operatorname{BS}
+            &=
+            \left\{
+            \nabla\phi:
+            \nabla\phi\text{ is normal to }\partial\Omega
+            \right\},
+            \label{eq:canon_biot_savart_kernel}\\
+            \operatorname{im}\operatorname{BS}
+            &\subsetneq
+            \operatorname{im}(\nabla\times),
+            \label{eq:canon_biot_savart_image_guard}
+        \end{align}
+        and the \(L^2\) bound
+        \begin{align}
+            \left\|\operatorname{BS}[\mathbf V]\right\|_{L^2(\Omega)}
+            \leq
+            \frac{\operatorname{OS}(\Omega)}{4\pi}
+            \left\|\mathbf V\right\|_{L^2(\Omega)},
+            \qquad
+            \operatorname{OS}(\Omega)
+            :=
+            \sup_{\mathbf y\in\mathbb R^3}
+            \int_\Omega\frac{d^3x}{|\mathbf y-\mathbf x|^2}.
+            \label{eq:canon_biot_savart_optical_size_bound}
+        \end{align}
+        The extended operator is bounded, compact, and self-adjoint on its
+        \(L^2\) completion.
+
+        \textbf{[CANON / FAR-FIELD GUARD].}
+        A general compact source gives
+        \(\operatorname{BS}[\mathbf V]=O(r^{-2})\).  If \(\mathbf V\) is
+        divergence-free and boundary-tangent, the leading moment cancels and
+        \begin{align}
+            \operatorname{BS}[\mathbf V](r)
+            =
+            O(r^{-3}).
+            \label{eq:canon_compact_fluid_knot_far_field}
+        \end{align}
+        Therefore the direct Biot--Savart velocity of one compact resolved vortex
+        knot is not a Newtonian monopole sector.  Any \(r^{-2}\) force claim must be
+        derived from a separately declared pressure/source, non-compact background,
+        singular-core, or boundary-supported mechanism.
+
